'''Strategic talk''' is how [[language]] can be used to maximize shared [[understanding]] by consciously and deliberalty to formulating talk, asking questions and giving answers, putting other's talk into our own words, using concrete example and telling stories to illustrate a meaning. This method of [[Organizational communication|organizational]] or [[business communication]] was created by Richard E. Heymen Ed.D.<ref>Heyman, Richard. Why Didn't You Say That in the First Place?: How to Be Understood at Work. San Francisco: Jossey-Bass, 1997. Print.</ref>
